reelection.”) In Trump’s warped view, being called to exercise leadership, empathy, and honesty during a pandemic is an “unfair” burden on his limited skill set. Compare Obama’s response during the Ebola outbreak. See Pacific Council on International Policy, “Lessons from the

Ebola Response for Dealing with Covid-19” (“The information that came from the Obama White House and the CDC during the Ebola epidemic was straightforward, direct, and honest”.) As Trump sees a shrinking path to victory, some are thinking

about the possibility that Trump will simply refuse to step down if he is defeated in November 2020. About a dozen panicked readers sent me a link to an article in Politico, “Trump sees a ‘rigged election’ ahead. Democrats see a constitutional crisis in the making.”

Before I discuss the article, let me acknowledge that we cannot dismiss the possibility that Trump will resort to voter suppression or that he will challenge popular vote results and Electoral College delegates. As always, we must mount countermeasures to prevent Trump and the

Republicans from taking unfair advantage. That said, the article is little more than speculation that Trump “might” try to hold onto power after he is defeated. Yes, he “might” try to do so. But the notion that his desire to remain in power will cause the collapse of a

constitutional order that has endured for two centuries seems remote. The article also worries that militias “might” try to overturn the result of the 2020 election. Again, anything is possible, and a few mentally disordered individuals might try to do something rash. But there

are about 450,000 National Guard in the US who are sworn to protect and defend the Constitution against all enemies, foreign and domestic. A few delusional gun owners are not a threat to a great nation.
There is a complete answer to the worries raised in the Politico article:

Don’t “squeak by” to victory in 2020. Trump is weakened and trapped in a cycle of self-destruction. In their first tussle, Biden has emerged on top, appearing to be more presidential, empathetic, and in control. Good. We should be reassured. @ScottWapnerCNBC @riskreversal

And Trump wonders why he is trailing among women, who bear a disproportionate burden in caring for parents and children. Joe Biden, on the other hand, wore a mask as he and Jill Biden laid a wreath in honor of American veterans killed in action. Trump mocked Biden’s decision to

My @realdonaldtrump "No Apologies" Tour continues: In a rational world, we would not be hostages to the mood swings of a dysfunctional president. But we are. It is a sad truth that his political psychosis has real-world consequences that affect millions. Trump was in high

dudgeon on Tuesday as he realized that his prospects for reelection are growing dimmer every day. Twitter has finally—finally—flagged two of his tweets to warn users that they are not true. See Politico, “In a first, Twitter adds fact-check labels to Trump tweets on

voting fraud.” (“Twitter tells users to “get the facts about mail-in ballots” on Trump tweet claiming California's mailed votes likely to be "substantially fraudulent.”) While Twitter’s tepid first step is long overdue, it has yet to respond to Trump’s grotesque

promotion of a conspiracy-theory about cable news host and former Congressman Joe Scarborough. Trump has retweeted a conspiracy theory that claims Scarborough is responsible for the accidental death of an intern in Scarborough’s congressional offices. (She suffered from an

undiagnosed medical condition that caused her to collapse and die at work.) The late intern’s husband, Timothy Klausutis, has pleaded with Twitter to prevent Trump from spreading the baseless conspiracy. See Mother Jones, “Trump Keeps Promoting a Baseless Murder Conspiracy Theory

, Despite Pleas From the Widower.” Klausutis wrote to Jack Dorsey, saying "I’m asking you to intervene in this instance because the President of the United States has taken something that does not belong him—the memory of my dead wife—

and perverted it for perceived political gain. " Trump’s cruelty in this instance is ghoulish. See The Atlantic, “The Malignant Cruelty of Donald Trump. (“The president is defaming the memory of a woman who died nearly 20 years ago—and inflicting pain upon her family
